Reasoning: The paper introduces a new measure of Public Information Complexity (PIC) for the study of multi-party computation protocols and their communication complexity and randomness requirements in the context of information-theoretic private computations. This involves concepts from information theory (cs.IT), computational complexity (cs.CC), cryptography (cs.CR), distributed systems (cs.DS), and data structures and algorithms (cs.DM).
